    "shortDesc": "Cellulitis, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Cellulitis, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Cellulitis is a bacterial skin infection that causes redness, swelling, warmth, and tenderness in the affected area, usually spreading across a larger region of skin rather than forming a localized bump. The infection occurs when bacteria enter through a break in the skin and multiply in the layers beneath the surface, and it requires antibiotic treatment to prevent it from spreading to deeper tissues or the bloodstream.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine doctors, primary care physicians, and infectious disease specialists commonly diagnose and treat cellulitis in urgent care and hospital settings. This code frequently appears on patient EOB statements because cellulitis is a common bacterial infection that requires prompt medical evaluation and typically results in antibiotic prescriptions or IV treatment.",
